{"source_key":"sha256-c55db1afbbe5d9067606af4f013482ee","record_index":1874,"record_hash":"sha256:52499207a61f5b93de3441899c446f2221724b2b7d10c9fe9b7780db80c92f12","timestamp":"2026-05-31T13:50:33.630Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 35639c\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1097\nOutput:\nExamples:\n\n```text\ncargo fmt --check\ncargo test -p <crate> <focused-test-name>\ncargo check -p <crate-or-bin> --features <feature>\ncargo clippy -p <crate> --all-targets --no-deps\npnpm test <package>\npnpm lint <package>\ngo test ./...\n```\n\nIf the baseline is already broken, fix or document that separately before\nstarting cleanup. A cleanup pass should not hide pre-existing failures.\n\n### Step 1. Main Agent Reads The Code\n\nThe main agent should read the target code first:\n\n- entry point files\n- orchestration files\n- domain modules\n- persistence/external-call modules\n- serialization/projection/rendering modules\n- nearby tests\n\nThen follow one concrete invocation through the subsystem. Keep this as a short\ncall-chain note, not a design document.\n\nDo not spawn subagents yet. The main agent needs enough context to judge whether\nsubagent feedback is useful or generic.\n\n### Step 2. Spawn Focused Review Subagents\n\nUse subagents for independent review, not implementation, at this stage. Give\neach subagent a narrow lens and ask for findings only.\n\nRecommended subagents:\n\n- **Deletion reviewer:** find fake extensibility, one-use helpers, dead fields,\n  ceremonial modules, and comments that repeat code.\n- **Boundary reviewer:** check that entry parsing, orchestration, domain logic,\n  persistence, external calls, redaction, and output stay separated.\n- **Execution reviewer:** follow one real invocation and report duplicated\n  normalization, surprising validation order, or side effects before validation.\n- **API/language reviewer:** check visibility, error boundaries,\n  ownership/cloning, naming, idioms, and public surface area.\n- **Test reviewer:** check whether tests protect behavior and whether any tests\n  are brittle implementation mirrors.\n\nOptional subagents:\n\n- **Security/privacy reviewer:** when public output, redaction, auth, local\n  paths, tokens, or raw payloads changed.\n- **Performance reviewer:** when parsi\n[TRUNCATED]\nusing boundary, or easy\n  simplification.\n- **Document only:** useful future concern but not cleanup-sized.\n- **Ignore:** speculative architecture, taste-only renames, or changes that make\n  the code larger.\n\nBe picky. A cleanup pass that accepts every suggestion becomes a rewrite.\n\n### Step 4. Make Small Behavior-Preserving Edits\n\nEdit in small groups:\n\n1. deletion and inlining\n2. naming\n3. visibility tightening\n4. boundary cleanup\n5. comment cleanup\n6. test cleanup\n\nRun formatting after edits. Avoid mixing a behavior fix with broad cleanup\nunless the behavior fix is tiny and directly discovered by the cleanup.\n\n### Step 5. Run Verification\n\nRun the focused checks again, then broaden only as needed.\n\nExamples:\n\n```text\ncargo fmt --check\ncargo test -p <crate>\ncargo check -p <crate-or-bin> --features <feature>\ncargo clippy -p <crate> --all-targets --no-deps\ncargo machete\npnpm test <package>\npnpm lint <package>\n```\n\nIf dependencies changed, run the dependency cleanup/checker for the ecosystem.\n\n### Step 6. Optional Second Review\n\nAfter edits, spawn one or two fresh subagents only if the diff is non-trivial.\n\nGood second-pass prompts:\n\n- \"Review only the cleanup diff. Did behavior accidentally change?\"\n- \"Look for new complexity introduced by the cleanup.\"\n- \"Check whether any tests became weaker or more implementation-coupled.\"\n- \"Check whether public output now leaks less than before.\"\n\nAvoid repeating the full review unless the cleanup touched many modules.\nRe-review has diminishing returns.\n\n### Step 7. Summarize The Result\n\nThe final summary should say:\n\n- what was removed or clarified\n- whether behavior changed\n- what validation ran\n- what suggestions were deliberately skipped and why\n- any remaining tradeoffs\n\nDo not claim the code is now future-proof. The win is that it is smaller and\nclearer now.\n\n## Validation Habit\n\nBefore and after cleanup, run the narrow checks for the target area. For\nbehavior-neutral cleanup, the best result is boring: smaller code, clearer\nnames, and the same behavior passing.\n","tool_name":"exec_command","tool_kind":"exec","tool_input":null,"exit_code":0,"outcome":"succeeded","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-31T13:50:33.630Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}